# Array construction type errors: literal element-type mismatch and length mismatch.
#
# A whole-value array literal is rejected when the element types are
# not uniform or when the literal length does not match the declared
# array length. Both errors are caught by the type checker before init
# state is consulted.
#
# Invariant: every function fires exactly one diagnostic. A regression
# here means literal type-checking no longer catches structural
# mismatches before lower passes run.
#
#   fn                    error               code
#   wrong_element_type    element i is wrong  TC-ArrayLitElementTypeMismatch
#   wrong_length          literal too short   TC-AssignmentTypeMismatch

# ---------- element type mismatch: one element has the wrong integer width ----------

# The declared type is [i64; 2] but element 1 is i32. The checker
# fires TC-ArrayLitElementTypeMismatch before any assignment proceeds.
fn wrong_element_type() {
  a: [i64; 2];
  entry:
    a = [1i64, 2i32];
    return
}

# ---------- literal length mismatch: fewer elements than declared size ----------

# The declared type is [i64; 3] but the literal supplies only two
# elements. The resulting RHS type is [i64; 2], which does not match
# [i64; 3], so TC-AssignmentTypeMismatch fires.
fn wrong_length() {
  a: [i64; 3];
  entry:
    a = [1i64, 2i64];
    return
}
